align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Proportionality should be adopted between the designation of conservation sites and the assessment of development proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RenewableUK welcomes the opportunity to submit evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the Environmental Audit Committee with regards to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Marine Conservation Zones. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RenewableUK is the trade and professional body for the UK wind and marine renewables industries. Formed in 1978, and with over 650 company members, RenewableUK is the leading renewable energy trade association in the UK. Wind has been the world's fastest growing renewable energy source for the last seven years, and this trend is expected to continue with falling costs of wind energy and the urgent international need to tackle CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emissions to prevent climate change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Key points</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RenewableUK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supports the development of a network of ecologically coherent Marine Protected Areas (MPAs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">endeavours</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to positively contribute to the achievement of this objective. The offshore renewables industry is gaining an increasing understanding of the impacts of its activities in the marine environment and has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">played a constructive role in the designate Marine Conservation Zones (MCZs), providing data and information to the bodies involved in the process and in some cases contributing to working groups with the aim of developing management measures collaboratively with the relevant statutory nature conservation bodies. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that further refinement and improvement of the designation process for MCZs could help meet both conservation and industry development objectives. If we are to fulfill Government policies on economic growth and sustainable development whilst meeting the objective of creating a network of ecological coherent MCZs, it is important that efforts are made to address the following key areas which have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">characterised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the process to date.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RenewableUK asks that the following aspects are taken into account before the next tranche of MCZs sites is considered for designation:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Detailed m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">anagement measures should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">clearly set out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> alongside proposals for MCZs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">During the 2013 consultation on the designation of the first tranche of MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> specific management measures were not part of the evidence informing the consultation. This meant that existing or future users of the sites did not know which activities would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">restricted with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in each site, or what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mitigation measures would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">required. This level of uncertainty can have significant implications for project feasibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and timelines</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">A clear and objective socio-economic assessment methodology should be developed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There is uncertainty on how the regulatory decision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">making</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">process will consider environmental impacts alongside socio-economic impacts, and it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">currently unclear which information will be needed and how this will be used in the process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Impact Assessment accompanying the 2013 consultation has shown that socio-economic impacts have been underestimated during the designation of the first tranche of MCZ sites and we urge that these aspects are given the same importance as environmental ones. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impact Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the new sites must be realistic and take full account of future renewable energy developments or there is a risk that legally binding renewables targets could be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">jeopardised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Proportionality should be adopted between the designation of conservation sites and the assessment of development proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - The recent MMO guidance on Marine Conservation Zones and Marine Licensing (April 2013) makes clear that the burdens of assessment applied to development will be similar to the ones applied to conservation sites</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also envisag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a clear balance between the application of the precautionary principle and the adoption of a risk based approach. This should include establishing a baseline without the need for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">excessive and costly surveys and assessments (limiting the extent of these phases through more effective screening and scoping stages) and utilizing similar standards of evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for all proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is also important that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the large amount of environmental data provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d by industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not result in disproportionately large numbers of development sites being designated as MPAs.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RenewableUK continues to be supportive of the objective to create </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a network of ecologically coherent Marine Protected Areas (MPAs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, considering its fulfillment as a key element to combine conservation objectives and the definition of a clearer context for the development of offshore renewables. We are sure that DEFRA and regulators share the same vision and therefore wish that our suggestions are taken into account in the interest of all parties.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Please note, we understand this inquiry to be focused on Marine Conservation Zones as designated under the Mar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ine and Coastal Access Act 2009. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e have therefore made no comment on the separate and distinct process for designation and management of marine protected areas under the Marine (Scotland) Act 2010.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">23 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>